english:
  title: In Praise of Three Sages of the Later Han
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I was reading the histories and came upon the annals of Emperor Ling of the Later Han, where all who were called the wise and worthy of the empire were branded as members of factions and utterly destroyed without trace. Alas, had calamity ever reached such depths? Among them, those few who kept themselves pure and measured in speech, untouched by such ruin, were but a handful indeed. I have selected the most illustrious of these and composed this praise.

    Lin Zong of Taiyuan—known by the name Guo Tai—possessed vast learning and bright discernment. When he first journeyed to Luoyang, wise men like Wang Fu and Kong Rong marveled at him upon a single meeting. Through their introduction to Li Ying, his reputation spread among all. A thousand carriages escorted him as he sailed homeward. He traveled far and wide, instructing others, so that even the humble and lowborn were moved by his virtue. He comforted Yuan, admonished Yun, befriended Mao Rong, and honored Qiu Xiang as his teacher. In a broken sieve he discerned character; in a cast cup he perceived the human heart. He refused Song Chong, yet heeded only the words of the young one. Fan Fang, who understood this, kept himself whole in a turbid age—a teacher to all men, a light of the Way. Yet his equal has never been seen. O Master, how great thou were!

    The young Xu Zhi of Yuzhang was his native land. He ate only what his own labor produced; his family poor, he tilled the soil himself. Though people revered his virtue, he would not answer the emperor's summons. When Chen Fan invited him, Chen Fan set forth but one mat of honor to receive him. Many times officials sought him for service, yet he would not go—what matter was it? When called, he did not come; instead he took his books to mourn at another's house. When all the renowned scholars gathered to pay respects at Huang Qiong's funeral, at first none knew of Xu Zhi. Yet afterward, all were amazed. Ji Wei pursued him, greeting him as an old friend. But when asked of state affairs, he spoke only of farming and harvest. Comparing his silence to Lin Zong's restraint, who can say which showed greater wisdom? O how excellent! His fragrant virtue shall be honored through the ages.

    Qiu Xiang of Chenliu was one whose conduct was pure and whose words were few. At forty, none knew his name; his village regarded him as worthless. Yet when finally he entered service as magistrate of Putingtown, his moral influence transformed Chen Yuan, and only then did the world come to know his name. At first, Yuan's mother did not love her own son and reported him as unfilial. Qiu Xiang was startled, reproaching himself for his failure to teach. Yet through sincere words, he reconciled mother and child, and their love and filial piety became perfect. When Wang Huan of Kaocheng reduced his own stipend to provide funds and sent Yuan to the Grand Academy, his studies were completed. Lin Zong himself took him as teacher, and thus his Way shone forth. Yet he declined office and spent his remaining years at home. O what a hero of the age!
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Party Purge' (党锢) refers to the political persecution during Emperor Ling's reign when scholars and officials deemed threats to the eunuch faction were systematically eliminated.
  - key: ''
    value: Lin Zong (Guo Tai) is a legendary figure of moral authority whose judgment of character was trusted throughout the empire.
  - key: ''
    value: The anecdote of the broken sieve and cast cup refers to moments where character is revealed through unexpected circumstances.
  - key: ''
    value: Xu Zhi's refusal of official position in favor of humble farming represents the classical Confucian ideal of virtue existing independent of worldly rank.
